Burn the Playbooks
This morning, I saw a tweet [ https://substack.com/redirect/463165c9-3ff5-4=
10a-931a-26af8fac4f06?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that said =E2=80=9Cthe modern world seems to crush geniuses=
=2E=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Last week, I read that elite college students can=E2=80=99t (or won=E2=80=
=99t) read books [ https://substack.com/redirect/4fdf1ea0-9542-4656-9e74-cc=
253828fb62?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ].
The week before that, a startup that recently got accepted to Y Combinator =
with an open source AI code editor got roasted for ripping off another YC t=
eam with an open source AI code editor.=C2=A0
These are all symptoms of the same disease: success has become overplaybook=
ed.
Playbooks give you the rules of the game and the steps you must follow to w=
in. They shrink the rich messiness of life down to an algorithm and turn pe=
ople into machines.=C2=A0
Ryan Yang-Liu=E2=80=99s argument [ https://substack.com/redirect/4ea6144b-5=
6a2-4b7f-90f3-ff16a2ed41e0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=93 based on his own experience =E2=80=93 is tha=
t math competitions take naturally very smart kids and focus them entirely =
on training for specific math tests. The game selects for people who are sm=
art enough and can train the most and learn the best. In the process, it ki=
lls polymaths.=C2=A0
The problem isn=E2=80=99t that kids are competing or studying hard, but tha=
t they=E2=80=99re narrowing.=C2=A0
One of the reasons kids can=E2=80=99t (or won=E2=80=99t) read full books an=
y more might be that books contain a lot of superfluous information that wo=
n=E2=80=99t be on the test. Mike Szkolka, a teacher quoted in the Atlantic =
article, explained that =E2=80=9CThere's no testing skill that can be relat=
ed to =E2=80=A6 Can you sit down and read Tolstoy?=E2=80=89=E2=80=9D, so te=
achers don=E2=80=99t make kids sit down and read Tolstoy. Or anything long =
and challenging.=C2=A0
The problem isn=E2=80=99t that they don=E2=80=99t know Tolstoy, specificall=
y, but that they might be missing out on the one book that ignites somethin=
g in them that makes them want to learn.
My friend Mike loves reading just for the sake of it more than anyone I kno=
w, because of The Agony and the Ecstasy [ https://substack.com/redirect/edb=
8646e-80e4-4490-a2b0-1a99ce3de87a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a 1987 biographical novel about Michelangelo t=
hat his AP European History teacher assigned as summer reading heading into=
 10th grade. =E2=80=9CIt hit me at the right time,=E2=80=9D he told me, =E2=
=80=9Caltered the intellectual trajectory of my life.=E2=80=9D Three or fou=
r years ago, Mike ran into that AP European History teacher at a wedding. H=
e told him how big an impact the book had made on him and asked if he still=
 assigned it. =E2=80=9COh goodness no,=E2=80=9D he replied, as if the quest=
ion itself were preposterous. =E2=80=9CThey could never handle it.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0
This carries into adult life, naturally, because how could it not? At a tim=
e when kids=E2=80=99 brains are most plastic, most able to soak in new idea=
s and make weird connections, we feed them playbooks. Then, they look for p=
laybooks =E2=80=93 for meaningless games to win =E2=80=93 everywhere.=C2=A0
The internet only figured out that that YC company was a fork of a fork aft=
er viscerally reacting to the cringiness of the original tweet. The tweet i=
tself is formulaic: quitting the big job, giving up the big salary (always =
include big numbers), AI something something, =F0=9F=A7=B5=E2=AC=87=EF=B8=
=8F, picture with the YC logo. And the fact that the kind of company that i=
s so formulaic in its tweet =E2=80=93 so devoid of creativity and originali=
ty =E2=80=93 and in the product itself =E2=80=93 a fork of a fork, so devoi=
d of creativity and originality =E2=80=93 got into YC hints that YC has bec=
ome a game more than a signal.=C2=A0
There is a pattern that repeats itself over and over. Maybe it=E2=80=99s al=
ways been this way. I wasn=E2=80=99t alive always, so I don=E2=80=99t know.=
 I know what it looks like today:=C2=A0
Someone does something for love of the game or out of pure curiosity.=C2=A0
They have success doing that thing.=C2=A0
Others see the success, deconstruct how they did it.=C2=A0
Others still repeat those same things, joylessly, without the original spar=
k.=C2=A0
Create a cheap shadow of the original.=C2=A0
I see this every day, in my particular line of work, every time a new start=
up hits my inbox promising to build X for Y but much better at Z in a $B ma=
rket. Playing startup. Startup Mad Libs=C2=AE. And I feel bad because you=
=E2=80=99re supposed to applaud the heroic effort required to start a start=
up, but a lot of these don=E2=80=99t feel heroic. They feel safe. And they =
feel doomed by that safety.=C2=A0
I bet you see it too, in yours.=C2=A0
Nothing great was ever created from a playbook.=C2=A0
Playbooks are the death of creativity and joy.
Sure, refer to the playbooks for non-core things.=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99ve used all of your creative powers to come up with a cure f=
or cancer and you want to follow a playbook for the FDA approval process, b=
y all means, do that.=C2=A0
But it seems as if too often, people are going through the FDA approval pro=
cess in hopes that it will lead them to the cure, metaphorically speaking.=
=C2=A0
They make the playbook the main thing. The playbook should never be the mai=
n thing. Playbooks are too easy to copy.=C2=A0
The sad part of the three examples I gave =E2=80=93 math tests, reading, an=
d copying code =E2=80=93 is that, very soon, AI will be able to do those th=
ings better than any human can. It kind of already can.=C2=A0
Announcing its newest model, o1, OpenAI wrote, =E2=80=9COpenAI o1 ranks in =
the 89th percentile on competitive programming questions (Codeforces), plac=
es among the top 500 students in the US in a qualifier for the USA Math Oly=
mpiad (AIME), and exceeds human PhD-level accuracy on a benchmark of physic=
s, biology, and chemistry problems (GPQA).=E2=80=9D
I don=E2=80=99t think AI will replace humans. My bet is that we=E2=80=99ll =
end up in a Goldilocks Zone [ https://substack.com/redirect/2b62a48e-df1d-4=
476-8202-88cbed40cf42?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ], where it gets really good at doing the things it does with=
out encroaching on the creativity that is humans=E2=80=99 greatest resource=
=2E=C2=A0
AI won=E2=80=99t replace humans, or beat humans at what we do best, unless =
we turn ourselves into cheap AIs.=C2=A0
AI will do math tests better than we can.=C2=A0
AI will do reading comprehension tests better than we can.=C2=A0
AI will copy code better than we can.=C2=A0
AI will follow playbooks better than we can.=C2=A0
Anything that we playbook becomes more legible to AI.=C2=A0
So we must burn the playbooks.
This is the real Butlerian Jihad, not destroying the machines, but destroyi=
ng the playbooks that would turn us into machines.=C2=A0
The challenge with an essay like this =E2=80=93 one in which I=E2=80=99ve s=
o vehemently railed against playbooks =E2=80=93 is that I can=E2=80=99t ver=
y well turn around and tell you exactly how to do that. That would be a pla=
ybook. You need to figure it out for yourself.=C2=A0
Maybe you want to read full, obscure books. Maybe you don=E2=80=99t. Maybe =
you want to do math problems for fun, or code for fun, or build something f=
or fun, or call in sick tomorrow to hike in the woods, or spend the next 73=
0 days straight working 18 hour days on the thing that you need to create b=
ecause the world needs it and you can=E2=80=99t stop thinking about it and =
even though it will probably fail you=E2=80=99re willing to sacrifice years=
 of your life for it, miss birthday parties and weddings and casual hangout=
s with your friends just to bring it into the world. Maybe you want to spen=
d more time with your kids and family and friends.=C2=A0
My own personal rebellion has just been to spend less time scrolling Twitte=
r =E2=80=93 maybe the clearest manifestation of how things go wrong when pe=
ople bend themselves to please an algorithm =E2=80=93 and more time reading=
 good books about anything that interests me. It=E2=80=99s been wonderful. =
I think it=E2=80=99s made me better at my job, too.=C2=A0
But I certainly don=E2=80=99t have all the answers, even for myself, let al=
one for you. Do something that makes you feel more creative, more alive, mo=
re human. Something that sets your brain on fire. Something that you love d=
oing more than anything else in the world. Something that no one can do jus=
t like you. Something that can=E2=80=99t be playbooked.=20
You are not a machine. Don=E2=80=99t act like one.=20
Thanks to Claude for editing.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with a Weekly Dose.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

