7f-90f3-ff16a2ed41e0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underli=
ne;">argument</a><span> &#8211; based on his own experience &#8211; is that=
 math competitions take naturally very smart kids and focus them entirely o=
n training for specific math tests. The game selects for people who are sma=
rt </span><em>enough</em><span> and can train the most and learn the best. =
In the process, it kills polymaths.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span=
>The problem isn&#8217;t that kids are competing or studying hard, but that=
 they&#8217;re </span><em>narrowing</em><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D=
"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;"><span>One of the reasons kids can&#8217;t (or won&#8217;t) read full=
 books any more might be that books contain a lot of superfluous informatio=
n that won&#8217;t be on the test. Mike Szkolka, a teacher quoted in the </=
span><em>Atlantic</em><span> article, explained that &#8220;There's no test=
ing skill that can be related to &#8230; </span><em>Can you sit down and re=
ad Tolstoy</em><span>?&#8201;&#8221;, so teachers don&#8217;t make kids sit=
 down and read Tolstoy. Or anything long and challenging.&#160;</span></p><=
p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The problem isn&#8217;t that they don&#8217;t know T=
olstoy, specifically, but that they might be missing out on the one book th=
at ignites something in them that makes them </span><em>want</em><span> to =
learn.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>My friend Mike loves reading just =
for the sake of it more than anyone I know, because of </span><em><a href=
=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/edb8646e-80e4-4490-a2b0-1a99ce3de87a?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">The Agony and the =
Ecstasy</a></em><span>, a 1987 biographical novel about Michelangelo that h=
is AP European History teacher assigned as summer reading heading into 10th=
 grade. &#8220;It hit me at the right time,&#8221; he told me, &#8220;alter=
ed the intellectual trajectory of my life.&#8221; Three or four years ago, =
Mike ran into that AP European History teacher at a wedding. He told him ho=
w big an impact the book had made on him and asked if he still assigned it.=
 &#8220;Oh goodness no,&#8221; he replied, as if the question itself were p=
reposterous. &#8220;They could never handle it.&#8221;&#160;</span></p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;">This carries into adult life, naturally, because how could it=
 not? At a time when kids&#8217; brains are most plastic, most able to soak=
 in new ideas and make weird connections, we feed them playbooks. Then, the=
y look for playbooks &#8211; for meaningless games to win &#8211; everywher=
e.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The internet only figured out that that=
 YC company was a fork of a fork </span><em>after</em><span> viscerally rea=
cting to the cringiness of the original tweet. The tweet </span><em>itself<=
/em><span> is formulaic: quitting the big job, giving up the big salary (al=
ways include big numbers), AI something something, &#129525;&#11015;&#65039=
;, picture with the YC logo. And the fact that the kind of company that is =
so formulaic in its tweet &#8211; so devoid of creativity and originality &=
#8211; and in the product itself &#8211; a fork of a fork, so devoid of cre=
ativity and originality &#8211; </span><strong>got into YC</strong><span> h=
ints that YC has become a game more than a signal.&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">There is a pattern that repeats itself over and over. Maybe it&#8=
217;s always been this way. I wasn&#8217;t alive always, so I don&#8217;t k=
now. I know what it looks like today:&#160;</p><ol style=3D"margin-top: 0; =
padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: bo=
rder-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">Someone does something for love=
 of the game or out of pure curiosity.&#160;</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8=
px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-lef=
t: 4px;">They have success doing that thing.&#160;</p></li><li style=3D"mar=
gin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, =
55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; paddi=
ng-left: 4px;">Others see the success, deconstruct how they did it.&#160;</=
p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-b=
ox; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; =
margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;">Others still repeat those same things=
, joylessly, without the original spark.&#160;</p></li><li style=3D"margin:=
 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-l=
eft: 4px;">Create a cheap shadow of the original.&#160;</p></li></ol><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;">I see this every day, in my particular line of work, every time=
 a new startup hits my inbox promising to build X for Y but much better at =
Z in a $B market. Playing startup. Startup Mad Libs&#174;. And I feel bad b=
ecause you&#8217;re supposed to applaud the heroic effort required to start=
 a startup, but a lot of these don&#8217;t feel heroic. They feel safe. And=
 they feel doomed by that safety.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I bet you see =
it too, in yours.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Nothing great was ever created=
 from a playbook.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Playbooks are the death of cre=
ativity and joy.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Sure, refer to the playbooks for non-=
core things.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If you&#8217;ve used all of your cr=
eative powers to come up with a cure for cancer and you want to follow a pl=
aybook for the FDA approval process, by all means, do that.&#160;</p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;">But it seems as if too often, people are going through the FDA =
approval process in hopes that it will lead them to the cure, metaphoricall=
y speaking.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">They make the playbook the main thin=
g. The playbook should never be the main thing. Playbooks are too easy to c=
opy.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The sad part of the three examples I gave &=
#8211; math tests, reading, and copying code &#8211; is that, very soon, AI=
 will be able to do those things better than any human can. It kind of alre=
ady can.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Announcing its newest model, o1, OpenAI=
 wrote, &#8220;OpenAI o1 ranks in the 89th percentile on competitive progra=
mming questions (Codeforces), places among the top 500 students in the US i=
n a qualifier for the USA Math Olympiad (AIME), and exceeds human PhD-level=
 accuracy on a benchmark of physics, biology, and chemistry problems (GPQA)=
